<seg id="13">The module & FSView; for & konqueror; provides another view for objects with the MIME-Type inode / directory on local files. it can be used as an alternative for the different symbol and text views to view the contents of your local file system.</seg>
<seg id="14">The peculiarity of & FSView; consists in representing nested folder hierarchies using a so-called tree map. tree maps allow the representation of the size of objects in nested structures. each object is represented by a rectangle, whose area is proportionally to its size. this size must have the property that the sum of the sizes of the child objects is smaller or equal to the size of the object.</seg>
<seg id="15">At & FSView, the size is the size of a file or folder, where the size of a folder is defined as the sum of the size of the entries in it. thus, large files can easily be detected even if they are far below in the folder hierarchy. therefore, & FSView can be seen as a graphical and interactive version of the & UNIX command.</seg>
<seg id="16">In & FSView, an entry in the Treemap display is a rectangle representing a file or folder in your filesystem. for easier navigation, the rectangles have useful color and labelling settings.</seg>
<seg id="17">The color of a rectangle that is switched over View Colour Mode can either represent depth for easy recognition of the nesting depth or the picture of another file property such as name, owner, group or MIME type.</seg>
<seg id="18">A rectangle can be labeled with the different properties of the corresponding file or folder. for each property, you can specify whether it is displayed at all, only if there is enough space to display or whether the area of subordinate rectangles occur. furthermore, you can specify the relative position of the label in the rectangle.</seg>
<seg id="19">For treemaps, the rule should be observed that the area is proportional to the size of the entry. at the Treemap in & FSView, this goal is not always met. frames are drawn to represent the nesting of entries, and this frame will need space, which is then lost to the subordinate entries. note that less space is lost for the frame when the rectangle is square.</seg>
<seg id="20">How splitting the area of an entry for the subordinate entries is left to the implementation. here it is always advantageous for caption and avoidance of space losses through frames in such a way that rectangles are created that are as square as possible. the best methods in this regard are rows, columns or recursive divisions.</seg>
